| accessdate  = 2012-11-23
| language    = [[English language|English]] 
| quote       = During the scorched-earth policy of the invading American militia during the War of 1812, all mills along the Erie shore as far as the Grand River were burned to the ground.  All, that is, except the mill belonging to John Backhouse, and Tisdale's mill in Vittoria.  Speculation has it that he was to related to key people in the United States.
}}
</ref>
During the [[War of 1812]] [[United States|American]] soldiers burned all the mills on Lake Erie`s north shore, from the [[St Clair River]] to the [[Grand River (Ontario)|Grand River]], except for the Backhouse mill, and one other.
According to Ron Brown, in <U+2033>The Lake Erie Shore: Ontario's Forgotten South Coast<U+2033>, Backhouse`s mill was skipped due to powerful connections within the USA.

The [[South Norfolk Railway]] reached Port Rowan in 1886.<ref name=ForgottenSouthCoast/>
It was acquired by the [[Canadian National Railway]], which operated it until 1965.

In 1970 [[Ontario New Democratic Party|New Democratic Party]] MPP [[Morton Shulman]] asserted that Port Rowan was the destination of secret meetings of [[mafia]] leaders.<ref name=WindsorStar1970-10-08>
